Materials Today: Proceedings

Volume 46, Part 11, 2021, Pages 5242-5247

A simulation study to evaluate and compare monofacial Vs bifacial PERC PV cells and the effect of albedo on bifacial performance

Author links open overlay panel,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.matpr.2020.08.632Get rights and content
Full text access

Abstract

Bifacial devices (bifacial cells and modules) have the capability of absorbing irradiation from its front as well as its rear side. This phenomena enables bifacial devices to produce a higher energy yield and consequently a reduction in the levelized cost of energy is achievable. Bifacial PV modules also have a higher energy density as they are capable of producing more energy for the same area. This paper presents a study on the modelling of a PERC bifacial cell performance under STC conditions (AM 1.5G) for different albedos. Along with that, a comparison between monofacial and bifacial cell when exposed to the same conditions is presented. A simulation has been carried out to determine the capability of c-Si PERC bifacial solar cells to derive power compared to its monofacial counterpart. The results show that bifacial solar cell produces more JSC and power relative to monofacial cell. The bifacial cell output is also measured for varying albedo, with higher power being derived at higher values of albedo. These results highlight the beneficial property of bifacial PV technology.

1. Introduction

Bifacial devices (bifacial cells and modules) have the capability of absorbing irradiation from its front as well as its rear side. This phenomena enables bifacial devices to produce a higher energy yield and consequently a reduction in the levelized cost of energy is achievable [1], [2]. Monofacial cells are able to collect the photons only from the front side, whereas their bifacial counterparts can simultaneously collect photons from incident and albedo light from front and rear sides [3]. The research in the field of bifacial devices dates back to the 1960â€™s. Cuevas et al. [4] demonstrated the effect of this phenomena by developing a setup to collect incident and albedo light by using a concentrator device to enhance the albedo part of radiation. Their experiment resulted in a 50% gain in electric power generation. Through these results, it was ascertained that bifacial cells have the capability to enhance the power producing capability and by extension the power density of PV devices compared to their monofacial counterparts, thereby realizing a reduction in the area related costs.
Bifacial PV modules also have a higher energy density as they are capable of producing more energy for the same area. This enables for smaller land use when installed in the field. Higher energy yield corresponds to higher monetary savings with time and thus leads to a lower payback period. The bifacial PV technology with glass-glass structure also shows lesser signs of degradation due to moisture, light induced and potential induced degradation. Thus, an increase in module lifetime and reduction in the maintenance costs which would be incurred during its period of operation. Apart from absorbing incident irradiation from rear as well as the front side, bifacial cells offer certain added advantages. These include (i) decrease in cell working temperature which leads to increased power generation due to increase in open circuit voltage (VOC) and (ii) decrease in the losses due to reduced amount of parasitic absorption usually occurring in the Al back surface and greater recombination at interface of Al back surface field (BSF) [5], [6]. The reduction in cell working temperature can be attributed to the lowering of infrared (IR) absorption in the cell due to the absenteeism of metallization on the back surface of the cell. Consequently, the bifacial PV cells operate at a significantly low temperature as compared to monofacial cells resulting in enhanced power output [7]. A case can be made for increase in module temperature when glass backsheet is introduced instead of a traditional back laminate resulting in higher thermal resistance [8], [9], [10], [11]. Thus, substantial understanding of the complex nature of bifacial output is essential and development of commonly acceptable standards is required for widespread acceptance of bifacial cells in the industry.
Bifacial module technology is slowly becoming more pervasive globally in the market. Workshops specific to industrial production enhancement, cost reduction, standardization techniques as well as other niche applications are organized. International Technology Roadmap for Photovoltaic anticipates a constant rise of the allocation of bifacial cells to over 15% of the cumulative by 2024 globally [12]. For glass-glass structure modules, it is expected that the market share will double. With cost estimates lowering to 1USD/W as per the U.S. Department of Energy expectations, reports point out that bifacial PV technology is slowly on the verge of emerging as the most significant technology for electricity production through solar energy [13]. However, a critical understanding of optimal module orientation (module tilt, spacing and elevation) is a prerequisite to move this technology from lab to the markets.
Fig. 1 presents the cross section of a common bifacial cell with crystalline silicon substrate. Both p-type cells and n-type bifacial cells consist of a metallization grid, which is open, engrossed on both sides of the cell, to absorb irradiance from both sides. N-type bifacial cell consists of a p+ emitter as a diffused layer and the back surface field is an n+ layer.
The structural difference between a bifacial PV cell and a monofacial cell is the rear contacts (Fig. 2). For a monofacial solar cell, the back contact (Ag, Al) is coated as a separate layer while for a bifacial solar cell, the back contacts are fabricated in the shape of an open metallization grid. The presence of a metallization grid enables the solar cell to absorb irradiation from the rear, enhancing the overall power production from the cell (Fig. 3).
Currently, the efficiency of bifacial cells if often calculated by separately defining the rear and front side efficiencies. To define the extent of relative performance of bifacial solar cell with respect to monofacial cells, various terminologies are used. Bifaciality factor is a repeatedly used parameter, which is adopted to relate the rear and front side performance of bifacial devices, and is describes as the ratio of rear side short circuit current density (JSC) and the front side short circuit current density [15].(1)BifacialityFactor%=JSC,rJSC,frontÃ—100

This paper presents a study on the modelling of a PERC bifacial cell performance under STC conditions (1 sun, AM 1.5G) for different albedos. Along with that, a comparison between monofacial and bifacial cell when exposed to the same conditions is graphically depicted. This article is divided into four sections. Section 1 presented a brief introduction about the technicalities of bifacial solar cell. 2 Methodology, 3 Results discuss the methodology followed for the simulation and the subsequent results obtained. A brief discussion on the results and prospective future possibilities are presented in Section 4.

2. Methodology

A c-Si PERC (Passivated Emitter Rear Contact) bifacial solar cell is modelled in SunSolve. PERC cells consist of a silver (Ag) front contacts followed by a SiNX ARC layer. The ARC is followed by a phosphorous diffused, boron doped silicon wafer that forms the P-N junction and an aluminium BSF. The rear screen printed Al coated grid is replaced by a rear Al grid. Table 1 presents a brief description of bifacial PERC c-Si cell technology.

The simulation to determine the characteristics and performance metrics of a bifacial solar cell is carried out on SunSolveâ„¢ [17]. SunSolve is an online calculator that simulates the behavior of a solar cell or module. The calculator contains a ray tracer that can simulate any number of textured layers of films. The calculator determines the reflection and absorption in each layer and the generation profile in the solar cell. It is also capable of determining the grid resistance and the current-voltage outputs. Sun Solve quantifies the losses and gains in each individual component. 3. Results

3.1. Monofacial Vs bifacial cell

The simulation is first carried out for a monofacial c-Si PERC solar cell. The input for both monofacial and bifacial cells has been kept the same. For this part of the simulation, the scaling factor for the rear side irradiation is chosen as 0.5. Fig. 3 shows the cross section of the rear of a monofacial and bifacial c-Si cell.
The difference between the rear structures of both the cells can be clearly seen. For monofacial cell, the rear electrode is applied as a coating on the entire surface of the solar cell, while for bifacial cell, the rear electrode is coated in a grid pattern. This is visible in the figure, with fingers on the rear of the cell.
A bifacial cell provides an added advantage of lower recombination losses resulting from lower parasitic absorption in the bulk of the solar cell. This is highlighted in Fig. 4(a), which shows the simulation results for parasitic absorption in the bulk of the solar cell for monofacial and bifacial solar cell. Consequently, lower parasitic absorption means higher absorption in the solar cell and thereby, higher external quantum efficiency of the bifacial solar cell (Fig. 4(b) and (c)).
For both the cells, the electrical parameters were obtained to verify whether the benefits shown the above figures can be extrapolated to electrical output. The comparative electrical behaviour of both solar cells has been plotted in Fig. 5. Through Fig. 5, it is clear that bifacial cell under same illumination provides better values of JSC and rated power. The simulation results for characterization of bifacial cell and monofacial cell highlights the positives of using a bifacial solar cell.

3.2. Effect of albedo

Albedo is defined as the percentage of sunlight reflected by a surface. Varying the albedo causes a considerable shift in the performance of the bifacial PV module. The performance shift can be attributed to the effect higher albedo has on the cumulative irradiance on the module (specifically the rear of the module). Janssen et al. [14] presented the effect varying the albedo has on the different components of irradiance by comparing a monofacial and bifacial module for Amsterdam (Fig. 6). The considerable effect higher albedo has on total irradiance and by extension, on bifacial PV performance, is clearly demonstrated. It should be noted that varying the albedo has negligible effect on the total incident irradiance for a monofacial module.
Albedo is dependent on the directional as well as the spectral nature of the incident irradiation and is not specifically an intrinsic property of the material used in cell. To characterize and quantify the albedo value, an albedometer is employed which measures the radiation while allowing for quantification of â€˜Î±â€™, the reflectance of solar irradiance and the cumulative solar radiation. An albedometer consists of class two pyranometer, two in number, along with thermal sensors. The upper pyranometer measures the GHI while the lower is used to record the radiation reflected from ground [18].
For the purpose of this simulation, the albedo is varied from 0 to 1 in fixed intervals of 0.25. The effect of albedo is studied for the bifacial solar cell. The results obtained are presented henceforth.
Fig. 7 represents the J-V characteristics obtained for the c-Si PERC bifacial solar cell under different albedo conditions. It can be observed from the plot that for bifacial cell with higher albedo, the J-V characteristics show better results than simulation runs with lower albedo. Fig. 8 presents the results for JSC, ISC and Power produced from bifacial solar cell under varying albedo. In all the results, the advantage of bifaciality is evident. These results conclude that higher albedo implies higher gains from a bifacial PV cell (Fig. 8).
The albedo is location dependent and varies from 0.1 to 0.8 (highest being from snow). The above results highlight the dependence of bifacial PV output on albedo. Thus, installing a bifacial PV module at locations with high value of albedo light can be highly advantageous.

4. Future scope of work

The advent of bifacial PV technology into the limelight has taken a considerable time as compared to other PV technologies. However, in the coming years, more focus will be given to bifacial PV technology as it provides an opportunity to yield more power from PV at a lower cost. But to achieve that, considerable amount of research still needs to be done. Quantification of bifacial performance as well as the characterization is a challenging aspect as a universal methodology to quantify the combined front and rear side irradiation is missing. Many models have been presented on the same, while the IEC recently presented a draft to characterize the PV modules which is under review. Along with that, accurate performance measuring methods and models need to be developed. Optimization of PV modulesâ€™ orientation, both stand-alone and farm level, is another area which needs to be addressed.

5. Conclusion

Bifacial devices (bifacial cells and modules) have the capability of absorbing irradiation from its front as well as its rear side. A simulation has been carried out to determine the capability of c-Si PERC bifacial solar cells to derive power compared to its monofacial counterpart. The results show that bifacial solar cell produces more JSC and power relative to monofacial cell. The parasitic absorption losses have also been quantified in the simulation and the results highlight the reduced parasitic absorption and consequently higher bulk absorption and EQE for bifacial solar cell due to absence of rear coating. The bifacial cell output is also measured for varying albedo, with higher power being derived at higher values of albedo. These results highlight the beneficial property of bifacial PV technology. In the coming years, increased attention will be provided to bifacial PV technology as it allows for an opportunity to yield more output from PV at reduced costs. But to achieve that, considerable amount of research still needs to be done.
